description.plain:
Originally formed 2004 in Baltimore, Maryland, Beach House is an American dream-pop duo consisting of of French-born Victoria Legrand (vocals, keyboards) and Baltimore native Alex Scally (guitar, keyboards).

Despite their summery name, Beach House creates music that is dark, dreamy, and alluringly hypnotic. In an interview with LiveAbout, Scally summarized their music as following:

I think that’s very much what the ‘beach house’ feel is: going off to a different world. It’s not really a vacation; vacation for me is when you go away, but you’re still thinking about all the things you’ve left behind.

Their self-titled debut released in early October 2006 via Carpark Records, the same label who also distributed 2008’s Devotion. Since 2010’s Teen Dream are Beach House signed to Sub Pop Records.

The duo’s critically acclaimed fourth studio album, Bloom, peaked at #7 on the Billboard 200 chart in June 2012, following its May release.

description.plain:
The Beach House members have a hard time describing their music and inspiration, but in a back and forth conversation about “10:37” found in a Pitchfork feature, their creative process for this “stretched-tape homage to toy soldier drum beats and a subject who casts no shadow” unravels in an indirect way:


“How do you describe that in language without sounding completely abstract and out-of-your-mind?” Legrand asks. “That’s how most moments of creativity feel—you almost can’t not use far-out language.”

“When you try to describe your creative moments, you veer off into a very unintelligible place of nonsense,” Scally says to her. “Because describing a moment of creativity is impossible.”

“Well, what am I supposed to say? I really don’t give a shit.” Legrand says this like she does, in fact, give a substantial shit.

“I almost think it’s not worth talking about because it’s so hard to articulate,” Scally offers in a consoling tone.

“All right, then I just won’t answer questions,” Legrand shoots back. “You can answer them.”

“That’s not what I was saying.”

“I know it’s not.”

Legrand then turns to me and adds, “He basically said I was unintelligible. I could be mildly offended by that—it doesn’t feel good when your partner tells you that you’re nonsense, but it’s the truth.”

“It’s not that,” Scally says, trying to dig himself out. “It’s just that I watch you go down these roads in your brain trying to be truthful, but there’s no concise answer.”

“It’s a lot easier to just feel it,” Legrand decides, already over it.

songs.title: 10 Mile Stereo

description.plain:
“10 Mile Stereo” is a deeper cut off of Teen Dream that packs an emotional punch. A slow, rolling riff introduces the song, and Legrand’s measured vocals draw the tension out until the song hits a minor explosion in the chorus.

Backed by an organ and drumbeat that is urgent by Beach House standards, the narrator denies the obvious (“it can’t be gone” when it surely is) in the chorus to give the song both a melancholy and hopeful tinge in turn.

The song was used in a Guinness ad, which aired only in Ireland [source: The FADER].

songs.title: 7 [Essay]
songs.embed_content: Read “7 [Essay]” by Beach House on Genius
songs.lyrics:
7 is our 7th full-length record. At its release, we will have been a band for over 13 years. We have now written and released a total of 77 songs together.

Last year, we released an album of b-sides and rarities. It felt like a good step for us. It helped us clean the creative closet, put the past to bed, and start anew.

Throughout the process of recording 7, our goal was rebirth and rejuvenation. We wanted to rethink old methods and shed some self-imposed limitations. In the past, we often limited our writing to parts that we could perform live. On 7, we decided to follow whatever came naturally. As a result, there are some songs with no guitar, and some without keyboard. There are songs with layers and production that we could never recreate live, and that is exciting to us. Basically, we let our creative moods, instead of instrumentation, dictate the album’s feel.

In the past, the economics of recording have dictated that we write for a year, go to the studio, and record the entire record as quickly as possible. We have always hated this because by the time the recording happens, a certain excitement about older songs has often been lost. This time, we built a “home” studio, and began all of the songs there.  Whenever we had a group of 3-4 songs that we were excited about, we would go to a “proper” recording studio and finish recording them there. This way, the amount of time between the original idea and the finished song was pretty short (of the album’s 11 songs, 8 were finished at Carriage House in Stamford, CT and 2 at Palmetto Studio in Los Angeles).

7 didn’t have a producer in the traditional sense. We much preferred this, as it felt like the ideas drove the creativity, not any one person’s process. James Barone, who became our live drummer in 2016, played on the entire record. His tastes and the trust we have in him really helped us keep rhythm at the center of a lot of these songs. We also worked with Sonic Boom (Peter Kember). Peter became a great force on this record, in the shedding of conventions and in helping to keep the songs alive, fresh and protected from the destructive forces of recording studio over-production/over-perfection.

The societal insanity of 2016-17 was also deeply influential, as it must be for most artists these days. Looking back, there is quite a bit of chaos happening in these songs, and a pervasive dark field that we had little control over. The discussions surrounding women’s issues were a constant source of inspiration and questioning. The energy, lyrics and moods of much of this record grew from ruminations on the roles, pressures and conditions that our society places on women, past and present. The twisted double edge of glamour, with its perils and perfect moments, was an endless source (see “L’Inconnue,” “Drunk in LA,” “Woo,” “Girl Of The Year,” “Last Ride”).

In a more general sense, we are interested by the human mind’s (and nature’s) tendency to create forces equal and opposite to those present. Thematically, this record often deals with the beauty that arises in dealing with darkness; the empathy and love that grows from collective trauma; the place one reaches when they accept rather than deny (see “Dark Spring,” “Pay No Mind,” “Lemon Glow,” “Dive,” “Black Car,” “Lose Your Smile”).

The title, 7, itself is simply a number that represents our seventh record. We hoped its simplicity would encourage people to look inside. No title using words that we could find felt like an appropriate summation of the album.

The number 7 does represent some interesting connections in numerology. 1 and 7 have always shared a common look, so 7 feels like the perfect step in the sequence to act as a restart or “semi-first.”  Most early religions also had a fascination with 7 as being the highest level of spirituality, as in “Seventh Heaven.”  At our best creative moments, we felt we were channeling some kind of heavy truth, and we sincerely hope the listeners will feel that.

Much Love,

Beach House3EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.title: All the Years

description.plain:
In an interview celebrating the 10-year anniversary of Devotion, Victoria reveals that she wrote this song while the band was sharing a practice space with a metal band – karma for when Victoria and Alex kept their old neighbors up practicing.

“We couldn’t hear what we were doing,” Scally says. Even so, they managed to write one of Devotion’s most tender songs there: “All the Years,” the dreamlike waltz at the album’s halfway point. “Let’s go on pretending / That the light is never-ending / So we still have the summers / Let’s be good to one another,” Legrand sings, offering a realistic but generous image of love (or any close relationship). “I’m very proud of that song,” she says now.

songs.title: All Your Yeahs

description.plain:
I believe the we in the song is either her present self and future self OR past self and present self talking to one another. In either case, the latter has knowledge of events that will occur on the former. It’s despite this knowledge, the latter tries to console the former. For the rest of the annotations, I’ll use present and future selves.

It is difficult to conceptualize ourselves as a different self than the day before but not as difficult to compare and see a difference in ourselves from today to 10 years ago. As we are the sum of our experiences, so has a person lived more each day. Few people have experienced anything without agreeing to do something or ‘our yeahs’.

songs.title: Auburn and Ivory

description.plain:
Track 5 on their self-titled debut album “Beach House”, released 2006, “Auburn and Ivory” broadcasts an oppressive, mesmerizing sound.

Could this song be about child abuse?

The language seems forced, running loops, refusing itself to an accessible interpretation; the morbid imagery of her “holding her bones by the fire” – with the color coding suggesting she is in fact “sacrific[ing]” herself to the flames, not any letter she wrote – stands in uncanny contrast to the picture of childhood innocence, drawn in the refrain through the coupling of “pony tails” and “ivory”.

songs.title: Beyond Love

description.plain:
The song takes a look at the mental state after a breakup – a heartbreak.
The song describes the destruction of looking at love in the romantic innocent way.
The narrator is allured to find out what love really is “since I didn’t understand”, in the pure sense it was presented. After the breakup, the narrator is heartbroken and the innocence is lost. The narrator is left only with her nightmares and feeling of loneliness once the “together” is lost and leaves a void.

The song could be hinting of a transition from believing in platonic to believing only in non-platonic love.

songs.title: Chariot

description.plain:
“Chariot” is one of the two previously unreleased songs, included in the Beach House’s compilation B-Sides and Rarities.

The song was released on May 17, 2017.

The other unreleased track is “Baseball Diamond”.

The music video contains footage of JFK riding in his “Chariot” before being assassinated. I’m sure there is more meaning to this song, but I recall Legrand saying somewhere in an interview that this song is about people not seeing the full picture to a story or something to that effect.

songs.title: Drunk in LA

description.plain:
When asked about “Drunk in LA” in interviews with Pitchfork and Stereogum, Legrand describes the song’s imagery as “an old starlet sitting in a bar in the dark by herself, someone who maybe had an insane life that no one will know about because there’s no one to talk to but themselves now,” and admits that the track is “full-on just my brain,” meaning that the composition of the lyrics were completely written by Legrand.

Scally also notes his appreciation for the songwriting. In an interview with Pitchfork, he says:

Those [lyrics] are my favorite. When she unveiled those lyrics, it was just like ‘holy crap.’ It’s just like each one is whip lashing you around all these abstract sensory places."

songs.title: Gila

description.plain:
“Gila” is a song about a Gatsby-eque lover who foolishly thinks that they can recreate the past. As a result this ends up damaging their future, and the future of their children.

Victoria compares “Gila” to “Heart of Chambers” because they both have “dark sass” and “witchy mysticism.”

It was somewhere in Mississippi that we put the pieces of ‘Gila’ together. All of these songs were written in different places, because we kept having to move.

The meaning of the word Gila is not exactly clear. It could be a reference to the poisonous Gila monster, or it could be that gila means “crazy” in Malay and Indonesian.

This song was sampled on The Weeknd’s “Loft Music”.

songs.title: Girl of the Year

description.plain:
“Girl of the Year” is inspired by one of Andy Warhol’s superstars, Edie Sedgwick, who was known as “Girl of the Year” in 1965. Legrand also notes in a Pitchfork interview in April 2018 that she would include Warhol’s Factory and Edie Sedgwick on a “mood board” for the album “7.”

In another interview with Stereogum, Legrand describes the track as having subjects including “the glamor and the destructive thing, that’s tied into [the] feminine side, but very dark and intense. More pink colors, or even crystal.”

The next song on the album, “Last Ride”, is also about one of Andy Warhol’s Superstars, Nico.

songs.title: Home Again

description.plain:
Victoria and Alex revealed that the process of turning “Home Again” from a demo to a finished song was a tense one. The struggle ended up being worth it, as the song serves as Devotion’s final track that nicely summarizes the album that came before it.

Victoria Legrand:


Alex and I were kind of fighting every day, just having crazy tension. I have this memory of being in the studio and feeling so stressed out and unsure.

The arguments weren’t personal. We’re trying to move in a direction, and we need to be on the same page. You have to be good at communicating. It always resolved, and I think that’s why we’re still working together. We have an ability to go to some dark places and climb our way out.”

songs.title: L’Inconnue

description.plain:
“L'Inconnue”, which directly translates to “the unknown” (female), is the first song sung in French by Victoria Legrand, who was also born in Paris.
The song may be a reference to a death mask that became a popular decoration in Paris in the late 1800s. A woman was found dead in the Seine, assumed to have taken her own life.
“The guy in the morgue was so taken by her [pleasant] expression that he made a plaster of it."

Anyway, in a Noisey interview, Legrand said that “it’s not about that specifically” and that the song’s lyrics were written before she heard about L’Inconnue de la Seine, describing the connection as “another weird, eerie spooky thing.”

The number seven is important on the band’s seventh album, simply titled 7. With this album, their discography contained 77 songs up to that point. On this song, the number 7 explicitly comes up with the seven girls mentioned. Victoria explains, “with that title there was a strange thing where the French aspect of the lyric was written before the realisation of, ‘What was that story of the woman in the Seine?’ It was a really eerie thing that occurred.” Alex continues:

We had other titles for it. ‘7’ was a one of them, but it was such a strange coincidence that Victoria wrote this part with the word ‘L’Inconnue’ in it and there was this thing that we completely forgot about. It was one of those titles that was meant to be."

Part of this song had appeared in a track for the short film This Must Be the Only Fantasy in 2013. In an interview with Stereogum, Legrand notes that the writing process for this song started “years ago,” and that “we always liked it, but we never found where it belonged … [This] particular song is an example of something from the past that never found its right moment, but for some reason the world of 7 — with its kind of futuristic, psychedelic, sacred universe — just made it fit.”

songs.title: Norway

description.plain:
On a journey through Norway in 2008, a Norwegian TV reporter joined them on a train from Bergen to Oslo and asked them to write a song during the duration of the trip and then recorded a video of them performing the song acoustically when they arrived to their destination.

Some have mistaken the chorus to be saying “your way” instead of “Norway.” It doesn’t seem to bother her that many of her metaphorical laden lyrics are misinterpreted.

Even when I see people have written some of my lyrics and they’re wrong, I’m never angry. I always just think, “Well, that’s what they wanted to hear I bet.” Because I think we hear what we want to hear. It’s like when someone says something and someone says “What?” And it’s like they pretend they didn’t hear it but they totally heard what the other person said. They just didn’t want to hear it at that time. Do you know what I’m talking about?
– Victoria Legrand

description.plain:
The second track on Beach House’s seventh LP is a slow ballad that seems to deal with a ceasing relationship.

Victoria Legrand said this song is a signature moment of their new collaborator Peter Kember, a.k.a. Sonic Boom, who worked on the production of this album:

That comet sounds that happens. It sounds like crazy sizzling stars exploding in slow motion. That’s the kind of thing he contributed.

These ideas also follow the theme of the opening track “Dark Spring,” which contains lyrics about dying stars and colliding worlds.

The song was recorded in 2017 and made available for early streaming through SubPop pre-order on April 27, 2018.

songs.title: Pink Funeral

description.plain:
An ode to Swan Lake, imagery of the overture and the curtain call starts the song off.



Swan Lake is the romantic tragedy of Prince Siegfried, who on a hunting trip encounters a flock of swans, falls in love with the Swan Queen, Odette, and swears his allegiance and undying love to her. As a result of a curse by the evil sorcerer Baron von Rothbart, Odette can only take human form between midnight and daybreak. Only faithful, true love can break the spell. To prevent his spell from being broken, von Rothbart transforms his own daughter, Odile, to look exactly like Odette. Dressed in black, she is presented to Prince Siegfried at his birthday party, and he thinks she is actually his beloved Odette. Thinking she is his Odette, Prince Siegfried swears his love for Odile, both destroying his future with the Swan Queen and dooming her to death. In most productions, the prince, distraught, commits suicide by jumping into the lake. But there have been many variations on a theme.



Pink Funerals seems to lean on the version from the 2010 body horror, phycological thriller and drama, Black Swan, where the Swan Queen, Odette jumps to her death.

The title of the song alludes to pink flowers, resembling elegance, grace and love commonly used at the funerals of women.

songs.title: Superstar

description.plain:
Superstar compares a failed relationship to a falling star. The first verse sets the tone for its end but throughout the song, the protagonist somewhat wrestles with the reality and reflects on how it was ‘something good’. So while the relationship is over, it was beautiful and to refer to the other as Superstar, suggests there is still love for the other.

Although not explicitly stated lyrically, it seems most likely the song depicts the narrative of two star-crossed lovers, a relationship which is thwarted by outside forces.

The rest of the song is descriptions of whats missing, which is what you would notice when doing an effortless activity like walking in the park.
